<TITLE> Democratic candidates fear US recession </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Myrtle Beach, South Carolina, Jan 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Democratic presidential candidates said on Monday they feared a US recession and criticized President George W Bush's proposed $145 billion fiscal stimulus plan as inadequate. "We could be sliding into an extraordinary recession unless we stimulate the economy immediately," candidate Barack Obama, an Illinois senator, said at a debate aired on CNN. His top rival, New York Sen. Hillary Clinton, said a drop in global markets was a "huge wake-up call," which she said was why she had modified her original proposal for a $70 billion stimulus. "The president's proposed stimulus package is not adequate," Clinton. "It is too little, too late and it doesn't give enough money to the people who are hardest hit by the increased costs of energy and everything else." Bush's plan would include tax cuts but the Democrats worried that millions of low-income Americans who do not pay income taxes would not qualify for any money. "They are completely left out of the stimulus package," said former North Carolina Sen. John Edwards
